summary.seg: The manuscript Nn.2.39 contains a humanistic copy of the Table-Talks by the Greek essayist Plutarch of Chaeronea (ca. 46 - ca. 120 AD), known as Συμποσιακὰ προβλήματα or Quaestiones Convivales (Moralia 46 = Plan. 78). The manuscript was copied at the end of 15th century or at the beginning of the 16th century by Petros Hypselas from Aegina, who was an associate of the scholar Demetrios Chalkondyles (ca. 1424-ca. 1511) in Florence, and after 1507 he taught Aristotle in Bologna as successor of Paolo Bombasios. The script is simple and clear, probably to meet the needs of Western readers. The copyist also shows that he is aware of the textual problems, and leaves some empty spaces in correspondence with the lacunae in the tradition. The manuscript was owned by the humanist Antonio Seripando (1476-1531), who inherited the library of Aulus Janus Parrhasius (1470-1522), and later entered into the collection of the English physician and book collector Anthony Askew (1722-1774). After his death, it was acquired by Cambridge University Library.

ff. i recto - 90v Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark:
Bull's head ( 90 60 ) in the middle of the folio comparable to Sosower Tête de boeuf 2 , dated the beginning of the 16th century.

supportDesc.foliation: [a-c] + i-ix, 1-53, 55-89, [90] + [d-f]. Early foliation in red ink in Arabic numerals, recto, top right from the second quire; number 54 is skipped. A modern foliation is added in pencil in Roman numerals, recto, top right to not-foliated folios of first quire.
supportDesc.collation:
The manuscript consists of 12 quires, 11 quaternions and a quinion:
Quires 1-118 ff. i recto - 80v
Quire 1210 ff. 81r-[90]v
Vertical catchwords in the hand of the scribe placed along the inner bounding line, reading from top to bottom on quires 5-8, ff. 31v, 39v, 47v, on quires 10-11, ff. 64v, 72v, 80v. Quire signatures in Arabic numeral in pencil from 4 to 11 on lower margin of first rectos of quires 5-12.
supportDesc.condition: In fair condition. Leaves are lightly yellow with age, mould deposits on endleaves. coloured staining (red) on f. 23v and (yellow) on f. i verso.

handNote.p: Petros Hypselas Hypselas, Petros : the manuscript was copied by the Greek scholar and scribe Petros Hypselas (RGK I 349) (active between the end of 15th and the beginning of 16th century) in a scholarly-calligraphical minuscule script in black ink.
Slanting slightly to the right, Hypselas' hand shows cursive-like ductus without variation in letter size. Ligatures and abbreviations are rare, common and very clear.

Beta is present in the bilobate and modern forms; tau and gamma are high, lambda is capitalized but small in size. The sigma telikon is present, the letters are often separated and easily recognizable, probably to facilitate reading by Western readers.
Breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or breathings, but the circumflex is traced in a single gesture together with the ypsilon or omega.

origin.p: The codex was copied by Petros Hypselas in Italy in the late 15th century or early 16th century.

history.provenance: The manuscript was owned by the Neapolitan humanist Antonio Seripando Seripando, Antonio, 1476-1531 (b. 1476, d. 1531), as stated in the note on f. i verso: Plutarchi quaestiones convivales, Graece, Antonij Seripandi ex Jani Parrhasii testamento. Seripando inherited the library of the humanist Aulus Janus Parrhasius Parrasio, Aulo Giano, 1470-1522 (b. 1470, d. 1522).

At Seripando’s death, his books passed on to his brother, Cardinal Girolamo Seripando Seripando, Girolamo, 1493-1563 (b. 1493, d. 1563), who in turn bequeathed his library to the Augustinian convent of San Giovanni a Carbonara in Naples . Before being declared 'Royal Library' by the King Ferdinand IV of Naples in 1792, the convent library was predated on several occasions and in some instances manuscripts and books were sold by the monks themselves.

The manuscript entered into the collection of the London lawyer Walter Clavell and later into the library of Anthony Askew (b. 1722, d. 1774) Askew, Anthony, 1722-1774 , physician and book collector. After his death, the manuscript was sold by G. Leigh and J. Sotheby in the auction of his library in 1785 (lot 592).
history.acquisition: The manuscript came to Cambridge University Library after the Askew's sale, and the University of Cambridge general bookplate (engraved by William Jackson in 1706-1707) was added on inside front board.
